CommonFields.Title: Preparation and Properties of Aqueous Castor Oil-based Polyurethane-Silica Nanocomposite Dispersions through a Sol-Gel Process
Author: Meier, M.
Xia, Ying
Larock, Richard C.
CommonFields.Location: Department of Chemistry, Iowa State University, Ames, Iowa 50011, USA

Mixing.Description: The castor oil (10.00 g), IPDI (6.23 g), DMPA(1.69 g),and 1 drop of DBTDL as catalyst were added to a fournecked flask equipped with a mechanical stirrer, nitrogen inlet, condenser, and thermometer. The reaction was carried out at 78°C for 1 h.
Mixing.Mixer: fournecked flask equipped with a mechanical stirrer

Additive.Description: 50mL of MEK was added to reduce the viscosity and prevent gelation.

Mixing.Description: The reaction was kept for another 2 h at 78°C.

Cooling.Description: Mixture allowed to cool down to room temperature.

Mixing.Description: TEA (3 equiv. per DMPA) was added to the PU solution and stirred for 30 min to neutralize all the carboxylic acid groups and to provide basic conditions for the following sol–gel process.

Additive.Description: The APTES was added and allowed to react with the excess amount of NCO groups at room temperature for 1 h.

Mixing.Description: Finally, water (150 mL) was added, followed by 1 h of vigorous stirring to effect dispersion and form silica nanoparticles through a sol–gel process.

Drying-Evaporation.Description: After removal of the MEK under vacuum, aqueous castor oil-based PU–silica nanocomposite dispersions were formed with a solids content of ~10 wt%.

MoldingInfo.Description: The nanocomposite dispersions were poured into a glass mold to dry at ambient temperature

Drying-Evaporation.Description: The nanocomposite dispersions were poured into a glass mold to dry at ambient temperature and then allowed to dry at 50°C for 24 h to obtain transparent films.

Transmission_Electron_Microscopy.Description: The morphology of the particles in the dispersion was observed on a transmission electron microscope (JEOL 1200EX). The dispersions were diluted to ~0.5 wt%, and then 3mL of the dispersion was deposited onto a carbon film grid. After drying, the samples were characterized.

Dynamic_Mechanical_Analysis.Description: The dynamic mechanical behavior of the nanocomposite films was determined using a TA Instruments DMA Q800 dynamic mechanical analyzer with a film tension mode of 1Hz and a heating rate of 5°C/min in the temperature range from –80 to 150°C.

Differential_Scanning_Calorimetry.Description: Differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) was carried out on a thermal analyzer (TA Instruments Q2000).

Thermogravimetric_Analysis.Description: Thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) of the films was carried out on a TA Instruments Q50 (New Castle, DE, USA). The samples were heated at a heating rate of 20°C/min from 50 to 650°C in air.

Nuclear_Magnetic_Resonance.Description: Solid state 29-Si NMR spectral analysis of the nanocomposites was performed using a Bruker Avance 600 spectrometer.
